NYT Web Traffic Analysis

Sean Mussenden

September 29, 2017

Introduction

In this analysis of simulated New York Times web traffic data from May 2012, we are seeking to discover patterns in how different user groups (age, gender, logged-in vs.not logged-in) behaved when visiting the site, as measured by ad impressions (page views) and click-through-rate. This page will walk a user through the analysis step-by-step, and include visualizations.

Reading in the data

Lets read in the weeks worth of New York Times web traffic, ad and click data, one csv per day. Store them as variables, nyt1 through nyt7.

nyt1 <- read.csv("csv/1_week_nyt/nyt1.csv", header=T)
nyt2 <- read.csv("csv/1_week_nyt/nyt2.csv", header=T)
nyt3 <- read.csv("csv/1_week_nyt/nyt3.csv", header=T)
nyt4 <- read.csv("csv/1_week_nyt/nyt4.csv", header=T)
nyt5 <- read.csv("csv/1_week_nyt/nyt5.csv", header=T)
nyt6 <- read.csv("csv/1_week_nyt/nyt6.csv", header=T)
nyt7 <- read.csv("csv/1_week_nyt/nyt1.csv", header=T)

Later on, it will be helpful to know which day of the week each of these observations came from. So lets add a new column to each of these called Day and set it equal to the day number in text, and another column called DayNumber, and set it equal to the day digit. The column Day and DayNumber dont currently exist, so adding it will append it after the last column.

nyt1$Day <- "One"
nyt2$Day <- "Two"
nyt3$Day <- "Three"
nyt4$Day <- "Four"
nyt5$Day <- "Five"
nyt6$Day <- "Six"
nyt7$Day <- "Seven"

nyt1$DayNumber <- 1
nyt2$DayNumber <- 2
nyt3$DayNumber <- 3
nyt4$DayNumber <- 4
nyt5$DayNumber <- 5
nyt6$DayNumber <- 6
nyt7$DayNumber <- 7

Now lets assemble our seven CSVs in to a single CSV, and store this new sheet. Note: as long as header rows are the same across sheet, this wont cause problems. Also, the header rows are not repeated with this method, unlike what happens with Excel if you tried to copy and paste sheets together. After we do this, to keep our workspace nice and tidy, we can remove the data sets we dont need. nyt1 - 7 are gone, leaving just nytweek.

nytweek <- rbind(nyt1, nyt2, nyt3, nyt4, nyt5, nyt6, nyt7)
rm(nyt1, nyt2, nyt3, nyt4, nyt5, nyt6, nyt7)

Getting a sense of the data

Lets take a look at our data set, and run some summary statistics. Some interesting things jump out:

  • The minimum age is 0, which is a cause for concern, since its unlikely that newborns are visiting the NYT site.
  • Because the mean gender is less than .5, we can tell there are more women than men in this data (0 = woman, 1 = man).
  • The mean number of ad impressions is 5, but the mean number of clicks (presumably on those ads) is minuscule, less than .1 percent.
  • The mean logged-in value is greater than .5 percent, meaning our data set has more logged-in users than not.

There are a ton of places where age is equal to zero. Since its almost certainly true that people who are 0 years old are not viewing the NYT site, we should remove those. Later on, though, it will be useful to analyze the data with those included. But when were analyzing by age, theyre meaningless. So lets take them out, but be sure to keep our original data intact. Well call this new data set nytweekno0.

nytweekno0 <- subset(nytweek, Age > 0)

Tidying, organizing the data

Now lets group each row/observation into an age group, using the cut function. Our age groups are <18, 18-24, 25-34, 35-44, 45-54, 55-64, 65+. We use the cut function and assign breaks. Were also going to group each row/observation into a click group whether they clicked through (1+ click) or didnt (0 clicks). We assign each of these cut functions to a variable name (agegroup, clickgroup) and then use column bind (cbind) to append them to the end of our existing data set.

nytweekno0 <- cbind(nytweekno0, agegroup = cut(nytweekno0$Age, breaks=c(0,18,24,34,44,54,64,Inf), labels=c("<18", "18-24", "25-34", "35-44", "45-54", "55-64", "65+")), clickgroup = cut(nytweekno0$Clicks, breaks=c(-1,0,Inf), labels= c("No Clicks", "Some Clicks")))

Lets also create a column for Clickthru rate called CTR, which is clicks divided by impressions. Because CTR doesnt exist yet in our dataset, its automatically added to the end of the existing table with this command.

nytweekno0$CTR <- nytweekno0$Clicks/nytweekno0$Impressions

For the first part of the analysis, we only need to look at a single day. So lets create a subset of the data that only includes the first day. Lets call this nytdayno0.

nytdayno0 <- subset(nytweekno0, Day == "One")

Visualizing, analysis

Load tidyverse and other viz libraries.

Lets run some summary statistics by age group to see what we discover. Several interesting points jump out:

  • The core NYT userbase appears to be middle-aged. The largest age group is 35-44 year olds, more than twice as large as 65+, and three times as large as under 18s.
  • While the mean number of impressions is fairly consistent at around 5 for each age group, theres a good bit of variation in the mean clicks for each group, which affects the CTR.
  • The mean click through rate for both young people (<18, with a mean age of 16) and old people (65+, with a mean age of 72) is substantially higher than people age 18 to 54. Each of those groups hovers around a mean click rate of .05, while its .13 for <18 and .15 for over 65+.
nytsummary <- nytdayno0 %>% 
  group_by(agegroup) %>%
  arrange(agegroup) %>%
  summarise(MeanAge = mean(Age),
            MeanGender = mean(Gender),
            MeanImpressions = mean(Impressions),
            MeanClicks = mean(Clicks),
            MeanSignedIn = mean(Signed_In),
            MeanCTR = mean(CTR),
            total = n()) %>%
  print(n = 10, width = Inf)

Lets drill in specifically on the behavior of logged-in users vs.non-logged in users. 0 is a not signed in user. 1 is signed in user. We need to go back to our original nytweek data set for this.

nytday <- subset(nytweek, Day == "One")

Lets create a natural language version of 0 and 1 for the logged in value Logged In Not Logged In and add it to the end of the data set. Lets also create a column for Clickthru rate called CTR, which is clicks divided by impressions. Because CTR doesnt exist, its automatically added to the end of the existing table.

nytday <- cbind(nytday, usertype = cut(nytday$Signed_In, breaks=c(-1,0,Inf), labels= c("Not Logged In", "Logged In")))

nytday$CTR <- nytday$Clicks/nytday$Impressions

Lets summarize our data based on usertype. While impressions are relatively consistent at around 5, the mean click through rate for logged in users is half the click through rate for not logged in users.

nytsummarycl <- nytday %>% 
  group_by(usertype) %>%
  arrange(usertype) %>%
  summarise(MeanAge = mean(Age),
            MeanGender = mean(Gender),
            MeanImpressions = mean(Impressions),
            MeanClicks = mean(Clicks),
            MeanSignedIn = mean(Signed_In),
            MeanCTR = mean(CTR),
            total = n()) %>%
  print(n = 10, width = Inf)

Now lets drill in on the behavior of men vs.women. Lets create a natural language version of 0 and 1 for the logged in value Female Male and add it to the end of the data set in column sex. Some interesting findings here: women were much more likely than men, on average, to click, though average impressions were essentially the same.

nytday <- cbind(nytday, sex = cut(nytday$Gender, breaks=c(-1,0,Inf), labels= c("Female", "Male")))

nytsummarycl <- nytday %>% 
  group_by(sex) %>%
  arrange(sex) %>%
  summarise(MeanAge = mean(Age),
            MeanGender = mean(Gender),
            MeanImpressions = mean(Impressions),
            MeanClicks = mean(Clicks),
            MeanSignedIn = mean(Signed_In),
            MeanCTR = mean(CTR),
            total = n()) %>%
  print(n = 10, width = Inf)

Now lets track movements across time. Lets add a new column to nytweek, using the grammar of tidyverse, using mutate() to calculate the clickthrough rate.

nytweek <- mutate(nytweek, CTR = Clicks/Impressions)

Now lets break down what, if any, difference there is by day across a single week.

Well create a new data frame (or a tibble in parlance of tidyverse) called nytsummary and group by day of the week, and calculate summary stats (means, across each category), plus a count of total observations. Heres what we see.

Theres almost no meaningful variation in average age (range 29.43 to 29.5). The gender profile if 0 is woman and 1 is man, an average under .5 indicates a larger percentage of women stays relatively constant across days, raging from .374 on day two, to .355 on day six. The mean impressions stays extremely constant at 5 on all days. And the mean number of clicks stays constant at .092. The percentage of signed in users if 0 is not signed in and 1 is signed in, then a mean over .5 means more signed in users than not signed in stays constant at .7. In fact, the only real variation across days present is the total number of users. That figure dips from a low of 370K on day 5 to a high of 765K on day 6.

nytsummary <- nytweek %>% 
  group_by(DayNumber, Day) %>%
  arrange(Day) %>%
  summarise(MeanAge = mean(Age),
            MeanGender = mean(Gender),
            MeanImpressions = mean(Impressions),
            MeanClicks = mean(Clicks),
            MeanSignedIn = mean(Signed_In),
            MeanCTR = mean(CTR),
            total = n()) 
  ggplot(data=nytsummary, aes(DayNumber,total)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = round(seq(min(nytsummary$DayNumber), max(nytsummary$DayNumber), by = 1),1)) +
  ggtitle("Mean clicks by day") +
  scale_color_fivethirtyeight() +
  theme_gdocs() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1)) + 
  xlab("Day") +
  ylab("Total clicks")
